        {
          "_params": {
            "showMeta": false
          },
          "title": "BACKGROUND",
          "meta": "By John Smith posted July 30, 2015",
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "header3",
          "_anchor": "header3-29"
        },
        {
          "text": "<p><b>Speech Act Theory\n</b></p><p>&nbsp;<i>“By saying something, we do something.”</i>\n----- Austin (1962)&nbsp;</p><p>Human societies and communities may be organized in various forms, but one thing we share is the privilege of language and interaction. For a long time, linguistic studies have been focused on the structure of languages (phonetics, phonology, syntax, and semantics), but human languages are more than that. In 1960s, philosopher Austin firstly proposed the idea of Speech Act; John Searle (yes, that Berkley philosophy professor being accused of sexual assault, but we’ll focus on his academic contribution here for today) then continued to develop this theory and firstly analyzed promising as a social act (Searle 1969). Searle defines promising as a subtype of commissive speech acts and is accomplished by a proposition that expresses speaker’s intention to do something in the future that the hearer wishes. A set of conditions and principles must be fulfilled to practice a sincere promise, such as the point or purpose of the act, the relative positions of the speaker and the hearer, the degree of commitment undertaken. \n</p><p>Politicians’ promises might be different (dramatic?) from ordinary people’s but should follow some basic linguistic formula of promises, such as lexical verbs and nouns of commitment (e.g. <i>promise, commit, vow</i>, etc.), modal verbs (e.g. <i>must, should, will</i>, etc.) and semi-modals (e.g. <i>be going to, want to, need to</i>, etc.). This project tries to explore the usage of these linguistic devices in politicians’ promises in important speeches. The current version focuses on two main questions: (1) Whether presidents’ preferences of promise-expressions have changed throughout U.S. history; (2) Do governors across the country have similar preferences of promise expressions?\n</p><p><b>Modals and modality system</b></p><p>Modality is a grammatical category that marks ability, necessity, permissions and obligation in utterances. The categorization of modality varies, this project follows Palmer’s (2001) modal system, which includes two main categories--propositional and event--and four subcategories--epistemic and evidential, as well as deontic and dynamic.  <b>Epistemic modality</b> indicates speakers’ stance on the factual status of the proposition, often marked by modal verbs in English such as <i>maybe, might, must</i>; <b>evidential modality</b> indicates speaker’s evidence for the factual status, marked by expressions such as <i>it is said, </i>and <i>I heard</i>; <b>deontic modality</b> expresses obligations or permissions from external sources, marked by modal verbs such as <i>must&nbsp;</i>and<i> should</i>, and semi-modal <i>have to, ought to</i>; <b>dynamic modality</b> indicates speakers willingness or ability that comes from individuals internal concerns, marked by modal verbs such as <i>will, can, </i>and<i> shall</i>.\n</p><p>Among these modalities, most deontic and dynamic modals are relevant to promises and commitment in interaction, some epistemic modals are also used in promises. In Modern English, it is recognized that there are nine central modal verbs, including<i> can, could, may, might, must, shall, should, will, would</i>. In addition, some words known as semi-modals also function as modals in interaction, such as <i>have to, want to, ought to, need to</i> (Biber et al. 1999, 73,483). \n</p><p>Based on the categorizations by Palmer (2001) and Biber et al. (1999), these common promise-relevant modals are grouped into<b> three types</b>: <b>volition (willingness)</b>, <b>obligation</b>, and <b>ability/possibility</b> (epistemic modals may and might, as well as would are less relevant to promises and are found no occurrence of commitment-expressing cases in the current dataset.) These modals, along with lexical verbs and nouns expressing commitment (such as <i>commitment, assure, promise</i>, etc.), will be searched as promise-expressions in the database. The frequency results will be analyzed and visualized to answer the two main questions in this project.</p>",
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "content1",
          "_anchor": "content1-2a",
          "_styles": {
            "DIV": {
              "color": "#7c706b"
