        {
          "_params": {
            "showMeta": false
          },
          "title": "Historical changes?&nbsp;<br>",
          "meta": "By John Smith posted July 30, 2015",
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "header3",
          "_anchor": "header3-2e"
        },
        {
          "text": "<p>The use of modals and verbs expressing promises might also corelate with important historical events. The most provident case is President Franklin D. Roosevelt’s inaugural speech in 1945. In this short speech (556 words), the normalized frequency of modals and verbs expressing commitment is as high as 40 per thousand. These expressions enables President Roosevelt to deliver his determination and encouragement to not only American citizens but also citizens of all nations during the Second World War. In contrast, President Franklin D. Roosevelt’s inaugural speech in 1941, however, is among the speeches containing least modals and verbs of commitment. In that speech, the president talked mostly about American spirits, such as independence and freedom.</p>",
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "content1",
          "_anchor": "content1-2v"
        },
